  "A physics teacher draws an acceleration-time graph showing a constant value of 3 m/s² from t = 0 to t = 6 s. If the initial velocity is 2 m/s, what is the final velocity?": "",
  "18 m/s — the final velocity equals the area under the acceleration-time graph alone: 3 times 6 = 18 m/s, without adding the initial velocity component": "",
  "3 m/s — the final velocity equals the value of the acceleration since velocity and acceleration are the same quantity when the motion has a constant rate": "",
  "6 m/s — the final velocity equals the elapsed time of 6 seconds, because the numerical value of elapsed time always matches the final velocity of the object": "",
  "20 m/s — the area under the a-t graph gives Δv = 3 × 6 = 18 m/s, so v = 2 + 18 = 20 m/s": "",
  "Area under a-t graph = Δv. Area = 3 m/s² × 6 s = 18 m/s. Final velocity = v₀ + Δv = 2 + 18 = 20 m/s.": "",
  "A student plots a position-time graph and observes the line curves steeply, then flattens. The student concludes the object accelerated then moved at constant velocity. A classmate says the object accelerated then decelerated. Who can determine who is correct from the graph?": "",
  "Both students are wrong — curved lines on position-time graphs only show constant velocity, and neither acceleration nor deceleration can produce a curved shape": "",
  "The classmate is correct — any curve that flattens on a position-time graph always represents deceleration, because all curving lines indicate the object is slowing down": "",
  "The student — a steep curve flattening to a straight line (constant slope) indicates acceleration followed by constant velocity, while a curve flattening to horizontal would indicate deceleration to rest": "",
  "Neither student can be correct — you would need a separate velocity-time graph to determine anything about the acceleration, since position-time graphs cannot show it": "",
  "If the x-t curve transitions from increasing slope to constant (nonzero) slope, velocity went from changing to constant — acceleration then constant velocity. If it flattens to zero slope (horizontal), the object decelerated to rest. The shape of the curve distinguishes the two interpretations.": ""
